ierc_1a: My anger stemmed from a domino effect of events. During the summer heading into my first quarter of college, my parents forced me to go on a trip to Las Vegas with them and, even though I was grateful for a trip not everyone gets to experience, I wasn't happy throughout the trip, because I had nothing to do. When I got back, my aunt invited me to go to the beach, but the Vegas trip tired me out and I wanted to do something I actually wanted to do. Unfortunately, my parents and aunt ridiculed me for not going, saying I was lazy. Then at night, when I wanted to eat at home, considering we at out everyday as Vegas, my parents again forced me to go with them. When we got back home, I was finally able to do something I enjoyed, video games. However, before I could even play for 30 minutes, my mom started yelling at me to go to bed and threatened to throw away my xbox, something I payed for myself. At that point I was extremely angry of having absolutely no control over my life. I was frustrated at never having a say in anything and never getting options. I was angry at constantly pushing aside my happiness and being ridiculed for just taking time to enjoy the things I liked.
ierc_1b: I was angry and sad at the same time. I was made of all the things that happened, but also sad that my parents didn't consider how I was feeling at the time. I didn't want to interact with anyone the next few days and locked myself in my room. I was tired of living a life my parents wanted, not the one I wanted.
ierc_2: My dad finally sat me and my mom down and we all had a discussion about why I was so angry. I told them about why those events made me feel like my life was being controlled, even though I was 18 years old already. My dad said he understood how all the events that happened could've made me feel restricted from simply living my own life. My mom didn't see it that way, but thats the difference between them. My dad sees and treats me like a man or an adult, while my mom still sees me as her little boy and thus treats me like one. My mom told me I was acting out and being disobedient. However, my whole childhood, I've foregone birthday parties with friends, events, basketball games, vacations to do things my parents wanted. I never enjoyed school, but I went to the library to study for my parents. My dad understood this, but also told me that isolating myself wouldn't fix any problems. So he made a deal with me. I would get to dictate my own life more, now that I was older. This meant a giving me a choice on whether I wanted to participate. This also meant not isolating myself any longer and communicating my anger sooner in the future and not letting it build up. My mom on the other hand, was now angry at me and my dad. She went on her phone and told my aunts how rude I was to want some independence in my life as an adult. I still live under her roof so I still abide by her rules, but having to live a life thats only in the realm of want my parents condemned seemed unfair to me.

At my latest tournament I played in, it was my first tournament in over a year and I had just began playing and practicing again after a week or so of not playing. I lost pretty badly against my opponent in the first round, I played terribly and felt like I had never played so bad before. I was incredibly frustrated and mad over my loss because I felt like I completely lost the way I typically play tennis.
ierc_1b: I was frustrated and agitated most of all. I was only a little sad but the emotions of anger and frustration completely overshadowed it.
ierc_2: Typically, on the way home from a tournament, about 10 minutes into the drive, my dad would begin speaking to me, asking me questions such as, "How do you feel", "What do you think happened during that match" and so on. At this point I'm calm but still deeply angry or frustrated as any normal person would be. My dad doesn't necessarily try to make me feel better after a match, he doesn't say things like "You played really good", or "You did your best". But this is because he knows that him saying such things won't make me feel better one bit, because I don't like getting praise after I lose, especially if I know I played bad. Instead, my dad searches for the reasons I lost, relays them to me, and tells me some things I can do better or things I need to work on.

I tried to take 3 different detours but they got closed when I go to them due to the weather getting worse. My trip ended up taking 11 hours of driving by myself instead of the usual 6 hours. Throughout the trip both my parents called me several times to check on me and keeping me company while I drove as I was very stressed out because I had a class to get to but I wouldn't make it due to all the traffic.
ierc_1b: I was really stressed out and close to having a breakdown while driving. I did cry when I was stuck in standstill traffic for about an hour with no signal as I felt really alone. I was also scared because I was alone and didn't know the roads and I had no signal so my maps would not route.
ierc_2: My dad called me several times and tried to give me directions based on where he last saw my location. He told me what freeway signs to follow. My dad also helped me by helping me word an email to my TAs and professors explaining why I would not be in class. My dad was at work but he got permission to stay on the phone as long as I needed as he did not want to leave me alone. He  told me about his day and tried to cheer me up by telling me funny stories. My dad even said a prayer with me for safe driving to calm me down and get me back safely as she knew I was extremely tired.

ierc_1a: I was upset because I was just feeling overwhelmed by all of the work and school that I am going to have to fully focus on for the next 2 weeks.
ierc_1b: I felt overwhelmed, anxious, and bitter that I couldn't do what I would rather do short-term. I was feeling uneasy about the future, and impatient about what I have to do to get where I want long-term.
ierc_2: My parents, specifically my mother, have helped me a lot with events like this that get me really anxious. As a preface, I am the kind of person that doesn't like to talk about myself and would rather not be the center of attention. However, whenever I am feeling like this, my mother does exactly what I need from her, and that's actively listen. My mom knows that part of my frustrations with stuff like this is looking too big picture, that if you think about the future too long and what you have to do you start to feel like you're drowning before you even start. What my mom does is listen to all the things that I am feeling stressed about, and tries to break it down into more steps, to focus me on what I should do now. She will say things to me sometimes like, 'even if you don't know all the details, you don't know all the things you have to get done, regardless of all that... you do know your next step, so take that'.
